summary: This FBI electronic communication from March 16, 2021, summarizes three NCMEC CyberTipline reports related to alleged child sex trafficking. The reports, submitted between 2019 and 2021, contain unverified claims linking individuals in Florida and Georgia to child trafficking, with one report specifically alleging that 'Epstein's group was still active' and identifying a person as the ringleader.

events.title: NCMEC Report on Child Sex Trafficking
events.description: NCMEC CyberTipline report #87492334 was submitted, reporting child sex trafficking. It alleged an individual in Gainesville, GA, was using another's identity and may have obtained custody of a child fraudulently.

events.title: NCMEC Report on Kidnapping and Cyber Torture
events.description: NCMEC CyberTipline report #85757143 was submitted by phone, reporting the use of cyber torture to access personal thoughts to find and take children. The reporter also claimed she was kidnapped in the Bermuda Triangle and that people were using time travel to steal from her.

events.title: NCMEC Report on Epstein Group Activity
events.description: NCMEC CyberTipline report #83658616 was submitted, reporting that 'Epstein's group was still active' and identifying an individual as the ringleader.

keyFacts: The FBI document summarizes three unverified NCMEC CyberTipline reports submitted between 2019 and 2021.
One report, from December 2020, explicitly claims 'Epstein's group was still active' and identifies a ringleader.
The reports contain highly speculative and unverified claims, including references to cyber torture, kidnapping in the Bermuda Triangle, and time travel.
All three reports were submitted from IP addresses located in Tampa, Florida, suggesting a common source.
The document indicates the FBI was reviewing these tips, but their credibility is not assessed within the provided text.
